==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mush
<hw>Mush</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Gael.
<ets>mus</ets>, <ets>muss</ets>, pap, porridge, any thick preparation of
fruit, OHG. <ets>muos</ets>; akin to AS. & OS. <ets>m⟦omac⟧s</ets> food,
and prob, to E. <ets>meat</ets>. See <er>Meat</er>.]</ety> <def>Meal
(esp. Indian meal) boiled in water; hasty pudding; supawn.</def>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mush
<hw>Mush</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moucheter</ets> to cut
with small cuts.]</ety> <def>To notch, cut, or indent, as cloth, with a
stamp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mush
<hw>Mush</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. short for
<ets>mush on</ets>, a corrupt of E. <ets>marchons</ets>, the cry of the
voyageurs and coureurs de bois to their dogs.]</ety> <def>A march on
foot, esp. across the snow with dogs; <as>as, he had a long
<ex>mush</ex> before him</as>; -- also used attributively.</def>
<mark>[Colloq., Alaska & Northwestern U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mush
<hw>Mush</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mushed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mushing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To travel on foot, esp. across
the snow with dogs.</def> -- <def2><pos>v. t. </pos> <def>To cause to
travel or journey.</def> <mark>[Rare]</mark> <mark>[Colloq., Alaska &
Northwestern U. S.]</mark></def2>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

